The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, May 28: The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) has expanded the definition of willful defaulters by including those companies which try to dispose of the mortgaged property without the knowledge of the bank or the lenders. According to the RBI, a company or an institution will be deemed a willful defaulter if it has defaulted in meeting its payment or repayment obligations to the lender even when it has capacity to honour them.                             
	 New York, May 28: Reliance Communications and South Africas MTN are working on a deal that will see the African firm gaining control of the Indian telecom giant, the Wall Street Journal reported today.                             
	 New Delhi, May 28: Telecom secretary Siddarth Behura is likely to meet the officials of BlackBerry maker Research in Motion tomorrow to sort out security issues over message encryption keys, which India is demanding from the Canadian company.                            
	 New Delhi, May 28: The telecom ministry is understood to have got the support of the finance ministry on the issue of participation of foreign players in 3G telecom services for which the policy is being framed.                            
	 Kolkata, May 28: Coal India Ltd (CIL) has entered into an agreement with MSTC Ltd, which will act as service provider for CILs e-tendering and reverse auction services.                            
	 New Delhi, May 28: Amid speculation that the RBI might further tighten money supply to tame inflation, the finance ministers adviser, Shubhashis Gangopadhyay, today cautioned against moving to a high interest rate regime as it can affect industrial growth.                            
	 Seoul/Beijing, May 28: General Electric (GE) has named South Koreas LG Electronics as a contender to buy its appliance business along with Chinas Haier Electronics Group, Mexicos Controladora Mabe and Turkeys Arcelik.                                                                                                                         
